<subSubSection id="1FE5655FFFE0416DCA81EF13FDEB274C" pageId="22" pageNumber="473" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE0416DCA81EF13FD7226FC" blockId="22.[151,1437,1626,1834]" box="[199,704,1663,1689]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE0416DCA81EF13FEE126FC" bold="true" box="[199,339,1663,1689]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">References:</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE0416DCB1CEF13FD7226FC" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[346,704,1663,1689]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="574036D4FFE0416DCA81EFCFFDEB274C" blockId="22.[151,1437,1626,1834]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">
<emphasis id="658BEAC6FFE0416DCA81EFCFFED026D8" bold="true" box="[199,354,1699,1725]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">Bioacoustics.</emphasis>
Tegmina (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE0416DCB9DEFCFFDAD26D8" box="[475,543,1699,1725]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1741,1765]" captionTargetBox="[161,1415,290,1715]" captionTargetId="figure-72@5.[151,1436,273,1718]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Left male tegmina of Acanthoplus discoidalis (CH8946), Acanthoproctus cervinus (CH8947), Hetrodes pupus (CHelb8948), Enyaliopsis bloyeti (CH8853), E. carolinus (CH8625), E. ephippiatus (CH7737), E. jennae (damaged; CH8267), Gymnoproctus rammei (CH8763), Eugasteroides loricatus (CH7352), Spalacomimus stettinenesis, S. talpa (CH7354), S. verruciferus (CH7188). Scale 5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392715" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392715/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), stridulatory file (
<tableCitation id="1A7D036FFFE0416DC8B5EFCFFCFA26D8" box="[755,840,1699,1725]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,239,332,356]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="TABLE 1. Body dimensions and characteristics of stridulatory files in Hetrodini" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101" pageId="22" pageNumber="473" tableUuid="0380665CFFF54178CAD1E820FC402101">Table 1</tableCitation>
), and spectrum of the song do not show large differences to the typical 
<taxonomicName id="90FF4D57FFE0416DCB35EFABFE6C2684" authorityName=", Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan" authorityYear="2010" box="[371,478,1735,1761]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="473" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Hetrodini">Hetrodini</taxonomicName>
pattern. The calling song (
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE0416DC941EFABFCD82687" box="[775,874,1735,1762]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="14.[151,250,1322,1346]" captionTargetBox="[156,1433,260,1291]" captionTargetId="figure-48@14.[151,1436,237,1299]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 10. Oscillograms of the calling songs in the genera Eugaster, Eugasteroides and Spalacomimus (figures of S. liberianus based on figures and data from literature; see text). A Eugaster guyoni, B Eugaster spinulosa, C Eugasteroides loricatus, D Spalacomimus liberianus, E Spalacomimus magnus, F Spalacomimus stettinensis, G Spalacomimus talpa, H Spalacomimus verruciferus, I Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392739" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392739/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">Fig. 10D</figureCitation>
; after 
<bibRefCitation id="336E4B25FFE0416DC9F4EFABFAAA2684" author="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R." box="[946,1304,1735,1761]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473" pagination="204 - 216" refId="ref17547" refString="Kowalski, K. &amp; Lakes-Harlan, R. (2013) The acoustic communication system in six species of armoured ground crickets (Orthop- tera: Tettigoniidae: Hetrodinae): commonalities and species-specific differences. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 252, 204 - 216. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. jcz. 2012.05.005" type="journal article" year="2013">Kowalski &amp; Lakes-Harlan 2013</bibRefCitation>
) consists of long series of syllables (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE0416DCBA2EF80FDA62763" box="[484,532,1772,1798]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">type</typeStatus>
B in 
<figureCitation id="CFC42A51FFE0416DC814EF87FD272763" box="[594,661,1771,1798]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1254,1278]" captionTargetBox="[158,1423,198,1221]" captionTargetId="figure-23@8.[151,1436,181,1231]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 5. Oscillograms of song types in Hetrodini. Song consisting A of long trills (Cosmoderus femoralis CH8627), B of broken trills (including transitions to long echemes; B1 Spalacomimus talpa, B2 Enyaliopsis jennae, B3 Enyaliopsis ephippiatus) or C of regularly repeated echemes (C1 Spalacomimus spec. near verruciferus, C2 Eugaster guyoni). 1-min-sections." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6392721" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6392721/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). With a mean duration of the series of more than 3 minutes it comes close to a continuous trill (song 
<typeStatus id="88448876FFE0416DCBB9EE7CFD9D274F" box="[511,559,1808,1834]" pageId="22" pageNumber="473">type</typeStatus>
A).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
